FILED SENATE
Mar 24, 2025
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
S.B. 462
SESSION 2025
PRINCIPAL CLERK
S D
SENATE BILL DRS45253-MCy-94
Short Title: Const Amend: Legislative Terms/Compensation. (Public)
Sponsors: Senator Burgin (Primary Sponsor).
Referred to:
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO AMEND THE CONSTITUTION OF NORTH CAROLINA TO MODIFY THE
3 LENGTH OF TERMS OF MEMBERS OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, THE
4 COMPENSATION OF MEMBERS OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY, AND THE
5 LENGTH OF THE SESSIONS OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY.
6 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
7
8 PART I. COMPENSATION AND ALLOWANCE MODIFICATIONS
9 SECTION 1.(a) Section 16 of Article II of the North Carolina Constitution reads as
10 rewritten:
11 "Sec. 16. Compensation Limitations on compensation and allowances.
12 (1) The members and officers of the General Assembly shall receive compensation for
13 their services the compensation and allowances prescribed by law. An increase in the
14 compensation or allowances of members shall become effective at the beginning of the next
15 regular session of the General Assembly following the session at which it was enacted.that is
16 equal to the average annual salary of public school teachers paid from State funds as determined
17 by the National Education Association which pay shall begin on July 1 of each fiscal year. The
18 members of the General Assembly shall receive per diem, subsistence, and travel reimbursement
19 that is consistent with similar allowances for State employees.
20 (2) The officers of the General Assembly who are not members of the General Assembly
21 shall receive for their services the compensation and allowances prescribed by law."
22 SECTION 1.(b) The amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section shall be
23 submitted to the qualified voters of the State at the statewide general election to be held on
24 November 3, 2026, which election shall be conducted in accordance with the laws governing
25 elections at that time. The question to be used in the voting systems and ballots shall be:
26 "[ ] FOR [ ] AGAINST
27 Constitutional amendment to set the annual salary for members of the General
28 Assembly in an amount that is equal to the average salary for classroom teachers and to set the
29 travel, subsistence, and per diem rates at the rates paid for State employees."
30 SECTION 1.(c) The State Board of Elections shall certify the results of the
31 referendum conducted under subsection (b) of this section. If a majority of votes cast on the
32 question are in favor of the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the Secretary of
33 State shall enroll the amendment among the permanent records of that office. If a majority of
34 votes cast on the question are against the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the
35 amendment shall have no effect.
*DRS45253-MCy-94*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 SECTION 1.(d) If the certification from the State Board of Elections under
2 subsection (c) of this section reflects that a majority of votes cast on the question are in favor of
3 the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the amendment set out in subsection (a)
4 of this section is effective upon certification.
5
6 PART II. TERM MODIFICATIONS
7 SECTION 2.(a) Article II of the Constitution of North Carolina is amended by
8 adding a new section to read:
9 "Sec. 25. Limitation of consecutive terms.
10 (1) No person shall be eligible to serve more than 16 consecutive years as a member of
11 the House of Representatives. A person disqualified by this section from election to the next
12 succeeding term as a member of the House of Representatives may not fill a vacancy in the House
13 during that term.
14 (2) No person shall be eligible to serve more than 16 consecutive years as a member of
15 the Senate. A person disqualified by this section from election to the next succeeding term as a
16 member of the Senate may not fill a vacancy in the Senate during that term.
17 (3) Terms of office beginning before January 1, 2027, shall not be considered for the
18 purpose of this section."
19 SECTION 2.(b) The amendments set out in this Part shall be submitted to the
20 qualified voters of the State at the statewide general election to be held on November 3, 2026,
21 which election shall be conducted in accordance with the laws governing elections at that time.
22 The question to be used in the voting systems and ballots shall be:
23 "[ ] FOR [ ] AGAINST
24 Constitutional amendment making the term of members of the Senate four years
25 beginning with Senators elected in 2028 and limiting members of the General Assembly to no
26 more than 16 consecutive years in a chamber."
27 SECTION 2.(c) The State Board of Elections shall certify the results of the
28 referendum conducted under subsection (b) of this section. If a majority of votes cast on the
29 question are in favor of the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the Secretary of
30 State shall enroll the amendment among the permanent records of that office. If a majority of
31 votes cast on the question are against the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the
32 amendment shall have no effect.
33 SECTION 2.(d) If the certification from the State Board of Elections under
34 subsection (c) of this section reflects that a majority of votes cast on the question are in favor of
35 the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the amendment set out in subsection (a)
36 of this section is effective upon certification.
37
38 PART III. SESSION LENGTH LIMITATION
39 SECTION 3.(a) Section 11(1) of Article II of the North Carolina Constitution reads
40 as rewritten:
41 "(1) Regular sessions.
42 (a) The General Assembly shall meet in regular session in 1973 and every two
43 years thereafter on the day prescribed by law.
44 (b) Odd-numbered years. – Beginning with the regular session in 2027, during an
45 odd-numbered year, the General Assembly shall remain in regular session for
46 no more than 120 calendar days, except that this period may be extended by
47 joint resolution once per regular session in an odd-numbered year for not more
48 than 10 calendar days. If the General Assembly, upon convening of the regular
49 session, meets initially for not more than two consecutive calendar days and
50 then adjourns for not less than 10 calendar days, that period of adjournment
51 shall be excluded from the 120 calendar days.
Page 2 DRS45253-MCy-94

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (c) Even-numbered years. – If the regular session meets in even-numbered years,
2 the General Assembly shall remain in regular session for no more than 90
3 calendar days, except that this period may be extended by joint resolution once
4 per regular session in an even-numbered year for not more than 10 calendar
5 days.
6 (d) Reconvened sessions called under Section 5 of Article III of this Constitution
7 and sessions required in response to orders of a court in which only matters
8 responding to the court order are considered shall be excluded from the
9 calculations of this section.
10 (e) Neither house shall proceed upon public business unless a majority of all of
11 its members are actually present.
12 (f) No valid action, other than a resolution of adjournment, may be taken by the
13 General Assembly in a regular session after the time limits prescribed in this
14 section have expired."
15 SECTION 3.(b) The amendment set out in this section shall be submitted to the
16 qualified voters of the State at the statewide general election to be held on November 3, 2026,
17 which election shall be conducted in accordance with the laws governing elections at that time.
18 The question to be used in the voting systems and ballots shall be:
19 "[ ] FOR [ ] AGAINST
20 Constitutional amendment limiting the length of regular legislative sessions to 120
21 calendar days in odd-numbered years and 90 calendar days in even-numbered years."
22 SECTION 3.(c) The State Board of Elections shall certify the results of the
23 referendum conducted under subsection (b) of this section. If a majority of votes cast on the
24 question are in favor of the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the Secretary of
25 State shall enroll the amendment among the permanent records of that office. If a majority of
26 votes cast on the question are against the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the
27 amendment shall have no effect.
28 SECTION 3.(d) If the certification from the State Board of Elections under
29 subsection (c) of this section reflects that a majority of votes cast on the question are in favor of
30 the amendment set out in subsection (a) of this section, the amendment set out in subsection (a)
31 of this section is effective upon certification.
32
33 PART IV. EFFECTIVE DATE
34 SECTION 4. This act is effective when it becomes law.
